Project Goal

As Computer Science and Finance majors, were fascinated by applying data science to real-world investing. In this tutorial, we analyze our personal stock portfolios using 10 years of price history and the FamaFrench 5-Factor Model (FF5) to explain and forecast returns relative to the US market.

Objectives:

  1. Estimate FF5 coefficients (alpha and ) for each portfolio.
  2. Interpret those factor exposures and the resulting alpha.
  3. Build predictive models to forecast future portfolio performance.
  4. Compare historical and simulated returns to evaluate which portfolio is likely to outperform.

Datasets:

  • FamaFrench 5-Factor data from Ken Frenchs Data Library
  • S&P 500 total return data from CapitalIQ
  • Individual stock prices via the Yahoo Finance API

Research Questions

This tutorial addresses two key questions:

  1. Historical Performance:
    Using the FamaFrench 5-Factor Model and 10 years of price data, which portfolio Ethans or Arzaans delivered superior risk-adjusted returns, and which factor exposures drove that outcome?

  2. Forecasted Performance:
    Based on Monte Carlo simulations of the FF5 factors (plus idiosyncratic shocks and a bootstrapped riskfree rate), which portfolio is projected to outperform over the next trading year, and what risks and factor tilts drive those projections?

Project Outline

To answer our research questions, we proceed in three main stages:

  1. FF5 Factor Data

    • ETL: Download and clean the daily FamaFrench 5-factor CSV from Ken Frenchs site.
    • EDA: Explore factor distributions, pairwise correlations, and trends over time.
    • Validation: Align and compare the FF5 market factor (Mkt-RF) against SPY total-return data to ensure consistency.

  2. Portfolio Data & Construction

    • ETL: Fetch historical adjusted-close prices via yfinance, set proper dtypes, and handle missing dates.
    • Assembly: Build dynamic, equal-weight portfolios for Arzaan and Ethan, automatically adjusting weights when new stocks IPO.
    • EDA: Compute and visualize portfolio return distributions, summary statistics, and correlation heatmaps.

  3. Modeling & Forecasting

    • Regression: Run multi-linear FF5 regressions ( and s) with K-Fold cross-validation on daily excess returns.
    • Simulation: Monte-Carlo sample the factors (plus idiosyncratic shocks and bootstrapped RF) to generate future return paths.
    • Evaluation: Summarize simulated outcomes (mean, variance, percentiles), plot mean trajectories, and draw insights on forecasted performance.

1. FamaFrench 5-Factor Data: ETL & Validation

In this section we will:

  1. Load the daily FamaFrench 5-factor CSV from Ken Frenchs Data Library.
  2. Clean & transform the data:
    • Rename the date column
    • Parse dates into a DatetimeIndex
    • Convert all factor and risk-free values from percentages to decimals
  3. Validate the dataset using the first factor as a bell-weather: Market Risk Premium Mkt-RF + RF against SPYs observed daily simple returns to ensure our FF5 series aligns with total market returns.

FamaFrench 5-Factor Regression

We model each portfolios daily excess return (R_{p,t} - R_{f,t}) as:

$$ R_{p,t} - R_{f,t} = \alpha_p \;+\;\beta_{p,\mathrm{MKT}}\,( \mathrm{MKT}_t - R_{f,t} ) \;+\;\beta_{p,\mathrm{SMB}}\,\mathrm{SMB}_t \;+\;\beta_{p,\mathrm{HML}}\,\mathrm{HML}_t \;+\;\beta_{p,\mathrm{RMW}}\,\mathrm{RMW}_t \;+\;\beta_{p,\mathrm{CMA}}\,\mathrm{CMA}_t \;+\;\varepsilon_{p,t} $$

where

$$ \varepsilon_{p,t} \sim \mathcal{N}\bigl(0,\;\sigma_{\mathrm{resid}}^2\bigr) $$

and the five factors are:

  • MKTRF (Market): excess return of the broad market over the risk-free rate
  • SMB (Small Minus Big): small-cap minus large-cap returns
  • HML (High Minus Low): value (high book-to-market) minus growth returns
  • RMW (Robust Minus Weak): high-profitability minus low-profitability returns
  • CMA (Conservative Minus Aggressive): low-investment minus high-investment returns

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): S&P 500 Benchmark

Before we proceed, let us look at how our data looks. To do this, we explore the historical behavior of the S&P 500 Total Return index to understand the market backdrop and validate our factor data.

  1. Plot the Total Return Index to visualize long-term growth and major market swings.
  2. Plot Daily Percentage Returns to highlight volatility and the random-walk nature of market moves.
  3. Summarize Daily Return Statistics (mean and standard deviation) to quantify the average drift and typical daily fluctuations.

To do this, we will primarily use line graphs/plots since we are using a time series:

Now that seems like an extremely noisy plot. That is why most Economists model stock price returns as a random walk. However, there is a drift (positive expected value) to this daily change, as shown below. This small drift gives it its distinictive exponential look and the variance explains why the market is considered so volatile (scary!).

To quantify the markets overall drift and volatility, we compute:

  • Average Daily Return: the mean of the daily price change.
  • Daily Volatility: the standard deviation of daily price returns, reflecting typical daily swings.

Validating FF5 Factors Against the S&P 500

Before using the FamaFrench series in our models, we verify that it truly represents the broad market:

  1. Align Dates: Restrict ff5_df and sp500_df to their overlapping trading days.
  2. Correlation Matrix: Compute correlations among the five FF factors, the risk-free rate, and the S&P 500s daily return.
  3. Key Checks:
    • Market Consistency: MKTRF + RF (total market return) should correlate very strongly ( 1.0) with SPY_Daily_Return.
    • Factor Relationships: Inspect off-diagonal entries to detect any unusually high inter-factor correlations that might signal multicollinearity.
In[]:
# Align FF5 & SPY on common trading dates
common_dates = ff5_df.index.intersection(sp500_df.index)
ff5_trimmed  = ff5_df.loc[common_dates]
spy_trimmed  = sp500_df.loc[common_dates]

# Build a single DataFrame for validation
valid_df = (
    ff5_trimmed[['Mkt-RF','SMB','HML','RMW','CMA','RF']]
    .assign(SPY_Daily_Return=spy_trimmed['SPY_Daily_Return'])
)

# Correlation matrix
corr_matrix = valid_df.corr()

# Check that MKTRF + RF  SPY
valid_df['MKT_Total'] = valid_df['Mkt-RF'] + valid_df['RF']
print("Corr(MKT_Total, SPY_Daily_Return) =",
      valid_df['MKT_Total'].corr(valid_df['SPY_Daily_Return']))

Corr(MKT_Total, SPY_Daily_Return) = 0.9958515860491032
In[]:
# In general, we can look at the heatmap to get an overview of each variable
# Create a mask to only display values/heatmap below diagnol so it is easier to read
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr_matrix, dtype=bool))

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(
    corr_matrix,
    mask=mask,            # hide True values (the upper triangle)
    annot=True,
    fmt=".2f",
    square=True,
    cbar_kws={"shrink": .7}
)
plt.title("LowerTriangle Only Correlation Heatmap")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The correlation analysis confirms that the FF5 market premium (MKTRF + RF) aligns almost perfectly with the actual S&P 500 daily return (correlation 0.99). This demonstrates that our FF5 series truly reflects broad market behavior.

The other factors also behave as expected over the past 15 years:

  • SMB shows a negative correlation with SPY (large-caps outperformed),
  • HML is slightly negative (growth beat value),
  • RMW is positive (profitability delivered a premium),
  • CMA is near zero (investment intensity had a modest impact).

These patterns match economic intuition and give us confidence that the FF5 dataset is valid for explaining and forecasting portfolio returns.

Portfolio Construction and Statistics

Using the adj_close DF, we can compute our daily price returns using a simple function pct_change(). We could also fill NaNs with 0 simply because if there were no returns for the day or the stock did not yet exist, it means we could not have it in our portfolio. However, that would impact our regression and analysis, as it would essentially make that part of the portfolio stagnant until the stock goes public.

Rather, let's deal with it more realistically. Where we only include it in our equal weighted portfolio if it's value is not NaN -- i.e., the stock is public. The portfolio automatically adjusts its weights when the stock is made public and we purchase it.

In[]:
# We create a series (DF) with the price changes
daily_rets = adj_close.pct_change()

# Then create an empty DF of our portfolio with daily returns only on tickers in our respective portfolio and if the stock is public
port_dynamic = pd.DataFrame(index=daily_rets.index)

# For each item in the portfolio
for owner, tickers in portfolios.items():
    # Broadcasting: take the rowwise mean, skipping NaNs automatically and constructing our portfolio only using available stock
    # This allows us to dynamically adjust the portfolio and weights to an equally weighted portfolio when a stock goes public
    port_dynamic[owner] = daily_rets[tickers].mean(axis=1, skipna=True)

# Cleaning if need be
port_dynamic.fillna(0, inplace=True)

# We now have one column per owner, where each days return is the average of only the available stocks that day.
print("Sample dynamicweight daily returns:")
display(port_dynamic.head())

Let's use this to find cumulative returns before we dive into our analysis just to see what we are working with. To do this, we will use continously compounded returns that uses the log to compound returns.

In[]:
log_rets = np.log1p(port_dynamic)                            # Daily log-returns
cc_cum   = np.exp(log_rets.cumsum()) - 1                     # Continously compounded cumulative returns
yrs      = len(log_rets) / 252                               # Years in sample

# Now let's use those to create some summary statistics
summary_cc = pd.DataFrame({
    "Cum. Return": cc_cum.iloc[-1],
    "Log Return": log_rets.sum()    / yrs,
    "Simple Return": np.expm1(log_rets.sum() / yrs),
    "Volatility": log_rets.std() * np.sqrt(252)
})

But one more thing. Diversification is an imperative concept in Finance - it is essentially the closest thing to a free lunch. Before we start predicting coefficients of risk and returns, we can have an initial crack at explaining why one portfolio might outperform another and understand systemtic vs idiosyncratic risk. So, let's look at correlation heatmaps between our portfolio's stocks and a measure of diversification.

The cell below cell computes each portfolios average pairwise correlation among its stocks and defines a diversification benefit as 1 - average correlation, which quantifies the overall risk reduction from holding multiple assets.

In[]:
# Combined correlation heatmap + diversification metric in one plot per portfolio
for owner, tickers in portfolios.items():
    if owner == "SPY":  # skip benchmark
        continue

    # 1) Compute daily returns and correlation matrix
    returns = adj_close[tickers].pct_change().dropna()
    corr = returns.corr()

    # 2) Calculate average pairwise correlation (off-diagonal)
    n = corr.shape[0]
    mask_offdiag = ~np.eye(n, dtype=bool)
    avg_corr = corr.values[mask_offdiag].mean()
    div_benefit = 1 - avg_corr

    # 3) Plot heatmap with metrics in the title
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.heatmap(
        corr,
        annot=True,
        fmt=".2f",
        cmap="vlag",
        center=0,
        linewidths=0.5
    )
    plt.title(
        f"{owner} Portfolio\n"
        f"Avg Corr = {avg_corr:.2%}, Diversification = {div_benefit:.2%}",
        fontsize=14
    )
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
    plt.yticks(rotation=0)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Suddenly, Ethan's outperformance makes a bit more sense. He is very concentrated into technology stocks which have historically outperformed the market by a lot. One other intersting observation to note: Arzaan's portfolio contains two perfectly negatively correlated stocks - TSLA and TSLZ. This is not naturally possible and was artifically created by using a short ETF for Tesla stock to hedge returns by Arzaan. Anyway, we must continue what we came here to do... see who will win in the future

3. Modeling & Forecasting

Finally, in this stage we will estimate factor exposures, quantify model fit, and generate forwardlooking forecasts:

  1. Regression: Align daily excess returns with FF5 factors and fit multilinear models via K-Fold CV to estimate each portfolios and .
  2. Validation: Report average R and RMSE across folds (and optionally test on a hold-out period).
  3. Monte Carlo: Simulate future factor paths (MV-Normal), add idiosyncratic $$ ~ $N(0,_r)$ and bootstrapped RF, then compute daily returns $r_t = + F_t + RF_t + $. Visualize and evaluate our results.
In[]:
# Defining a list of factors we will regress on
factor_list = ['Mkt-RF', 'SMB', 'HML', 'RMW', 'CMA']  # 5 factors
#factor_list = ['Mkt-RF', 'SMB', 'HML']  # 3 factors
#factor_list = ['Mkt-RF']  # 1 factors

Regression and Feature Coefficients

In[]:
# Ensure datetime indices already set on ff5_df and port_dynamic
owners  = list(portfolios.keys())
factors = list(factor_list)

# Align dates of portfolio and ff5
common = ff5_df.index.intersection(port_dynamic.index)
ff5_slice  = ff5_df.loc[common, factors + ['RF']]
port_slice = port_dynamic.loc[common, owners]

# Build regression table
data = ff5_slice.join(port_slice).dropna()
X = data[factors].values
Y = data[owners].subtract(data['RF'], axis=0).values   # excess returns

# K-Fold with contiguous folds (no shuffling)
n_splits = max(2, min(5, len(data)))
kf = KFold(n_splits=n_splits, shuffle=False)

results = {o: {'alphas':[], 'betas':[]} for o in owners}

# Getting results for each K-fold for each alphas and betas
for train_idx, _ in kf.split(X):
    Xtr, Ytr = X[train_idx], Y[train_idx]
    for i, o in enumerate(owners):
        mdl = LinearRegression().fit(Xtr, Ytr[:, i])
        results[o]['alphas'].append(mdl.intercept_)
        results[o]['betas'].append(mdl.coef_)

# Getting our Average across folds
rows = []
for o in owners:
    rows.append([o,
                 np.mean(results[o]['alphas']),
                 *np.mean(results[o]['betas'], axis=0)])

beta_cols = [f"Beta_{f}" for f in factors]
ff5_summary = pd.DataFrame(rows,
                           columns=['Owner','Alpha'] + beta_cols
                          ).set_index('Owner')

display(ff5_summary.style.format("{:.4f}"))

Validation: CrossValidated R & RMSE

Now, let's see how well FF5 Factor data explains daily excess returns for our portfolios. Using the same K-Fold splits, we will:

  • Compute R on each test fold to measure explained variance.
  • Compute RMSE on each test fold to gauge average prediction error (in daily return units).
  • Average R and RMSE across all folds for each portfolio to summarize model performance.
In[]:
# Prepare storage for R and RMSE across folds
r2_scores   = {o: [] for o in owners}
rmse_scores = {o: [] for o in owners}

# Loop over folds
for train_idx, test_idx in kf.split(X):
    X_train, X_test = X[train_idx], X[test_idx]
    Y_train, Y_test = Y[train_idx], Y[test_idx]

    # Fit & evaluate per portfolio
    for i, owner in enumerate(owners):
        model = LinearRegression().fit(X_train, Y_train[:, i])
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

        # Record metrics
        r2_scores[owner].append(r2_score(Y_test[:, i], y_pred))
        rmse_scores[owner].append(
            np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(Y_test[:, i], y_pred))
        )

# Build summary table
cv_summary = pd.DataFrame({
    'Avg R2':   {o: np.mean(r2_scores[o])   for o in owners},
    'Avg RMSE': {o: np.mean(rmse_scores[o]) for o in owners}
}).T

# Display with formatting
cv_summary.style.format({
    'Avg R2': '{:.2%}',
    'Avg RMSE': '{:.4f}'
})

Monte Carlo Simulation & Forecasting

With all our data, it comes down to this. We will use monte-carlo simulations to predict future performance using:

  • Residual volatility: Estimate each portfolios idiosyncratic from the regression residuals:
    $$ \sigma_{\text{resid},p} = \mathrm{std}\bigl(R_{p,t} - R_{f,t} - (\alpha_p + \beta_pF_t)\bigr). $$

  • Simulation setup: n_sims = 10 simulated paths, n_days = 252 trading days (1 year), rng = reproducible random generator

  • Factor paths: $F_{s,t}\sim\mathcal N(\mu_F,\Sigma_F)$ for each simulation $s$ and day $t$, where $\mu_F$ and $\Sigma_F$ are the historical FF5 factor mean and covariance.

  • Risk-free bootstrap: Sample daily RF from the empirical FF5 RF distribution to preserve its historical shape.

  • Idiosyncratic shocks: For each owner $p$, $varepsilon_{s,t,p}\sim\mathcal N(0,\sigma_{\text{resid},p}^2)$; note: beta and factors are vectors.

  • Total return for each sim (s), day (t), owner (p):
    $$ r_{s,t,p} = \alpha_p + \boldsymbol\beta_p \cdot \mathbf F_{s,t} + \mathrm{RF}_{s,t} + \varepsilon_{s,t,p}. $$

  • Cumulative simple returns:
    $$ R_{s,t,p}^{\mathrm{cum}} = \prod_{u=1}^t (1 + r_{s,u,p}) - 1$$

In[]:
# Before we jump into the monte-carlo simulation we also want to use idiosyncractic risk of our portfolios in our preditiction
X_mat = data[factors].values
ones  = np.ones((len(data), 1))

# So, let's just find the residual erros
resid_std = {}
for owner in owners:
    alpha  = ff5_summary.loc[owner, 'Alpha']
    betas  = ff5_summary.loc[owner, [f'Beta_{f}' for f in factors]].values

    y_hat  = alpha + X_mat @ betas          # predicted excess return
    resid  = data[owner] - data['RF'] - y_hat
    resid_std[owner] = resid.std(ddof=1)    # _resid
In[]:
# simulation settings
n_sims, n_days = 10, 252
rng = np.random.default_rng(2)

owners = ff5_summary.index.tolist()
factors = factor_list

# empirical factor stats
F = ff5_df[factors]
mu_F, cov_F = F.mean().values, F.cov().values

# simulate factor paths
sim_F = rng.multivariate_normal(mu_F, cov_F, size=(n_sims, n_days))

# draw daily RF from history (vector of shape (sims, days))
rf_hist = ff5_df['RF'].values
sim_rf  = rng.choice(rf_hist, size=(n_sims, n_days))

#  and 
alpha_vec = ff5_summary['Alpha'].values                    # (owners,)
beta_mat  = ff5_summary[[f'Beta_{f}' for f in factors]].values  # (owners, factors)


# excess  total return: r =  + F + RF + 
excess = np.einsum('sdf,of->sdo', sim_F, beta_mat)          # F

# build idiosyncratic shocks for each owner
eps = np.zeros_like(excess)
for i, owner in enumerate(owners):
    eps[:, :, i] = rng.normal(0, resid_std[owner], size=(n_sims, n_days))

total = excess + alpha_vec[None,None,:] + sim_rf[:,:,None] + eps
# cumulative simple returns, did this to be different from before for output. for a single year it is not that big of a deal
# however, for consistency sake if we had used continious returns before (we had not), then we would have used log returns here
cum = np.cumprod(1 + total, axis=1) - 1
sim_paths = {owners[i]: cum[:,:,i] for i in range(len(owners))}

# year-end summary (already 1-yr cumulative)
year_end = pd.DataFrame({o: p[:,-1] for o, p in sim_paths.items()})
summary  = pd.DataFrame({
    "Mean (1-yr)": year_end.mean(),
    "Var  (1-yr)": year_end.var(ddof=1),
    "5%":  year_end.quantile(0.05),
    "50%": year_end.quantile(0.50),
    "95%": year_end.quantile(0.95)
}).T
display(summary.style.format("{:.2%}"))

In the specific case above (we could always change the rng and get different results)

  • Expected Return & Risk
    Arzaans portfolio shows the highest average return (11.8%) but also the largest dispersion (variance 3.6%), whereas Ethans is lower-variance (2.8%) with a mean of 9.8%. SPY sits at 6.4% mean and 2.9% variance.

  • Downside Risk
    At the 5% worstcase level, Arzaans worst drawdown is 9.3%, compared to about 14% for both Ethan and SPYso Arzaans distribution has less extreme left-tail risk.

  • Median Outcome
    Ethans median (50%) return is 12.0%, slightly above Arzaans 10.5%, indicating a higher most likely outcome for Ethan despite his lower mean.

  • Upside Potential
    In the top 5% of scenarios, Arzaan can see gains up to ~42%, well above Ethans ~33% and SPYs ~32%, reflecting a fatter right tail.

Arzaans portfolio is the most spread outit offers the highest average and upside at the cost of greater volatility. Ethans portfolio sits between SPY and Arzaan: it delivers a high median return with moderate variance, while SPY remains the most stable but lowest-returning benchmark.

However, our biggest takeaway from this entire exercise is that it is almost impossible to predict the short-term performance of stocks. We tinkered with every metric, and yet the model changed in unexpected ways. Randomness was the biggest driver of any sustainable result and that is why we believed that monte-carlo simulations were the best simulation tool to accompany our linear regression.

Conclusion & Next Steps

Summary of Findings

  • Historical Attribution: Ethans portfolio outperformed Arzaans and both outperformed the SPY over the past decade by combining full market exposure (1), strong qualitygrowth tilts (negative HML, positive RMW), and a meaningful stockpicking alpha (10 % p.a.). Arzaan earned a respectable 14.5 % p.a. but missed many systematic premiums. However, both also had extremely signficant alpha.
  • Model Fit: Crossvalidated R of 85 % for Ethan versus 76 % for Arzaan confirms the FF5 model explains more of Ethans returns. Lower RMSE for Ethan (0.44 % daily) versus Arzaan (0.60 %) underscores this.
  • Forecast Insights: MonteCarlo simulations project Ethans median oneyear return at 12 % with moderate downside (14 % at 5 %), while Arzaans higher mean (11.8 %) comes with fatter tailsboth downside and upside.

Conclusions

  • Ethans qualitygrowth megacap profile captured the key factor winds (market, profitability, growth) and generated persistent alpha, resulting in superior risk-adjusted performance.
  • Arzaans speculative smallcap basket delivered higher upside potential in extreme scenarios but carried greater idiosyncratic risk and underperformed on average relative to factor benchmarks.

Next Steps & Extensions

  1. OutofSample Testing: Hold out the most recent quarter or year to assess true predictive power on unseen data.
  2. Alternate Factor Models: Incorporate momentum or liquidity factors to see if they explain any residual variation (especially for Arzaans portfolio).
  3. GARCHEnhanced Simulation: Replace the MVNormal assumption with GARCHbased volatility forecasts to capture volatility clustering and fat tails.
  4. Dynamic Allocation Rules: Explore factortilted or riskparity weighting schemes instead of static equal weight.
  5. Transaction Costs & Practical Constraints: Model the impact of rebalancing costs, slippage, and position limits to gauge realworld implementability.

By combining academic factor models, robust crossvalidation, and forwardlooking simulation, this tutorial illustrates a comprehensive end-to-end data science workflowand yields actionable insights into portfolio construction and forecasting.
